Question 3.1.2 (Euclids Problem)

Parallelogram: Area=x*y*sin(theta); x=base; y=height; theta=angle

Triangle: Area=(1/2)*x*y*sin(theta); x=base; y=height; theta=angle

Constraint: x+y=alpha. x>=0, y>=0

The parallelogram's optimal solution has an angle exactly the triangle's angle.

Area of a parallelogram with affine adjustment:
 
  Area = (Triangle total area)-(Triangle A area)-(Triangle B area)

       = (Triangle total area)-(Square ratio x/alpha)*(Triangle total area)-(Square ratio (x-alpha)/alpha)*(Triangle total area)
       = [1-(x/alpha)*(x/alpha)-(x-alpha)*(x-alpha)/(alpha*alpha)]*(Triangle Total area)

Maximal Area of a parallelogram:

  dArea/dx = 2*(alpha-2*x)/(alpha*alpha)

        x* = alpha/2

Parallelogram area compared to a triangle:

  Area = [1-(x*/alpha)*(x*/alpha)-(x*-alpha)*(x*-alpha)/(alpha*alpha)]*(Triangle Total area)

       = (1/2)*(Triangle Total Area)

